se a retuning of the Resonant Gate using the bone tablet and heartseed sliver.\",\n        \"Decide whether to demand Orun Ves’s removal, force a binding accord under public oath, or expose all and risk immediate unrest.\",\n        \"Sound the Gate’s corrected chord and coordinate with Watch, Bonewrights, and the Order to calm the city.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Matron Sere Kall\", \"lines\": \"Stand where the bone remembers, Rogan, and let the floor carry your stance into the marrow of those who would forget their debt to the city. I will hold the frame as I have held bridges in storms, but the span we cross today is woven of breath and belief, not stone and sinew. Speak in the measure of true instruments: bone for strength, glass for clarity, word for binding, and give no inch to rattling coins masquerading as authority. Remember that no iron may be drawn here, so you must cut with steadiness and patience, and your edge will be the truth all can hear. If your voice falters, lean upon the Gate’s long note and upon the names of those who thirsted while ledgers fattened; they will lend you courage without asking interest.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Orun Ves\", \"lines\": \"Weather comes and goes, Mr. Kettlebone, and clever men do not mistake a passing gust for a season turned. Rumor is a cheap wind, while ledgers are the mountains that teach it where to break, and I have charted these currents for longer than your scars have itched. Papers can be coaxed to sing false, and cullet can hum in any key if you warm it with the right furnace, so forgive me if I do not kneel at the altar of a single page and a pretty shard. The city has always loved a villain it can name because it lets the rest of us keep our little grifts and call them necessities, and perhaps that comfort is what you truly sell today. Choose your witnesses carefully, for the bone remembers every footstep, and you may discover that your echo pleases the mob in the square while offending the ribs that actually hold the sky above them.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Rogan Kettlebone\", \"lines\": \"I grew up in the Under-Ribs where the Gate’s hum was lullaby and alarm both, and I learned early that debts and droughts both come due, no matter whose hand signs the permit. I carried water under sun that peeled skin and escorted barges through reed-mist where voices lied in the shapes of my loved ones, and I learned what truth costs when it is not convenient. You tuned our ribs to your profit, Factor, called it efficiency, and let the poor drink air while mirrors sang your virtue in the Temple’s oculus, and I did not forget the taste of that dust. I bring the page, yes, but I bring also a chord that does not bend around silver, a shard that remembers the storm before your tariffs named it theirs, and a sliver of patience from a heart that might yet warm this city without burning it. Today I choose witnesses with more eyes than your ledgers have lines, and they are called Marrowhold, and they are ready to hear a note that does not flatter the throat that sings it.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Isha Velroon\", \"lines\": \"The dome hears everything spoken beneath it, and it leans most kindly toward those who have tasted hunger with the humble and still choose to share their bread. I have listened to the ink on that page with the reliquaries awake, and they shivered in a way that prayers do not soothe, for the note runs against the grain of the vows we bless. Mercy has a weight, yes, and it must sit in the same bowl as justice lest the scale crack, but mercy unguided by truth is only delay, and truth unlighted by mercy is a blade drawn in a house where iron is forbidden. We can bless an accord that keeps water unowned and oaths transparent, we can help the Watch hold ribways without using silence as a cudgel, and we can let the Bonewrights tend the strings so no purse can retune them in secret. If we do this, let us do it under the sun we revere, with mirrors turned not to blind but to brighten, and let us swear it where children can hear and remember.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Legate Tharn Corvell\", \"lines\": \"I have kept curfews with a bone whistle and the promise of a dawn that would still find our roofs overhead, and I have buried men who heard a different promise and did not live to test it. My officers can hold a line or bite their tongues, but not both if the square seethes and the echo-pipes spit contradiction, so give me clarity and I will give you quiet streets without the stink of fear. If you hand me a truth we can broadcast, I can set rook-kites to colors that calm, I can station constructs at bridges to be seen and not to strike, and I can walk ranks without feeling like I am lying to men whose pay I am already behind on. But if all you give me is spectacle and insinuation, then the first thrown bottle will write a law none of us wished to read, and the ribs will remember screams instead of a steady note. So tune your Gate, warrior, and give me a chord my Watch can march to without stepping on the city’s throat.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Prelate Lys Amon\", \"lines\": \"The Hollow Sun is a veiled light, and we are its keepers, not its owners, just as we must be keepers of the city’s thirst without folding our fingers around the cup. I have watched men use sanctity as a cloak for their appetites, and I have seen men spit upon sanctity because it did not match their appetites, and neither feeds a child. We must be precise: we will bless water oaths that are public and provable, we will renounce dominion over rations as a lever of politics, and we will call heresy only what seeks to unmake the city, not what seeks to mend it. If the Gate’s chord is retuned so its warning cannot be bought, then our mirrors will reflect that vow, and we will let the light judge us by whether we keep our word in drought as well as in rain. Speak, then, with the patience you carry in that sliver, and let