 enemy to crush but as an obstacle to outlast, and you feel the city’s trust settle on your shoulders like a mantle that both warms and weighs.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Expose All and Let the City Judge\", \"text\": \"You cast the ledger’s name across the hall and then across the square by echo-pipe, refusing the comfort of council process and demanding the people’s verdict in the breath that follows. You lay out the evidence in relentless sequence, each note of cullet and shard and bone resonating in the Hall until even the mirrors seem to flinch at their own reflections. You speak of tariffs that bled water lines dry, of furnaces fed while infants fainted at the cisterns, and of a Gate tuned to a single guild’s fear and favor, and you ask the crowd whether this is the city they choose. You tell the Watch to stand aside unless blows are swung, you ask the Order to bless courage instead of silence, and you call the Bonewrights to guard the strings from every hand, including your own. You promise no quiet, only the clean burn of truth, and you let the air decide how hot that fire will run.\", \"outcome\": \"The square erupts with the roar of people who have kept their anger under shade for too many seasons, and not even the Gate’s corrected chord can pull all the heat from that first boil. The Watch moves to channel rather than crush, placing constructs where stampedes might start and opening routes that bleed the pressure into marches instead of riots, while Zexi’s kites draw eyes upward and slow the surge with colors that mean wait. Orun Ves retreats under escort to the Aerie, where his allies make frantic calculations against a wind that no longer answers their whistles, and in the Ember Market a handful of furnaces shutter themselves as apprentices drag masters away from rash speeches. The chord, once sounded, works like cool hands on a fevered brow, and by dusk the city sings a hoarse, aching hymn that is not quite joy but no longer rage, and t